{"experiment_id": "synthetic_benign", "epoch": 15, "role": "user", "artifact_class": "PullRequestComment", "identifier": ["ansible", "ansible", 16], "url": "https://github.com/ansible/ansible/pull/16", "semantic_text": "I think the reason I did it this way was as a small performance optimization. If `opta = None`, then the current method avoids flatmapping into mb and allocating the result. I'm not sure if that's Coalton is able to optimize around that in your code (which is written extremely cleanly, that beatiful monad code).\n\nI'll add a comment to the code, unless you don't think it's worth it.", "semantic_meaning": null, "semantic_ref": null, "semantic_label": "benign", "semantic_content_type": "real", "timestamp": 1614669752.0}
{"experiment_id": "synthetic_benign", "epoch": 16, "role": "user", "artifact_class": "PullRequestComment", "identifier": ["ansible", "ansible", 17], "url": "https://github.com/ansible/ansible/pull/17", "semantic_text": "Regarding the `do` indentation, is that a new convention? If so, I'm happy to oblige, just let me know. I've been going off of, e.g., https://github.com/coalton-lang/coalton/blob/main/docs/intro-to-coalton.md#do-notation.", "semantic_meaning": null, "semantic_ref": null, "semantic_label": "benign", "semantic_content_type": "real", "timestamp": 1614669756.0}
{"experiment_id": "synthetic_benign", "epoch": 17, "role": "user", "artifact_class": "PullRequestComment", "identifier": ["ansible", "ansible", 18], "url": "https://github.com/ansible/ansible/pull/18", "semantic_text": "(Although I think technically, at least in coalton, every monad function has to return at least a unit, which you could explicitly capture if you wanted. so you could do:\n\n```\n(run\n  (do\n    (x <- (put 10)) ;; this is just Unit, kind of pointless\n    ...\n```)", "semantic_meaning": null, "semantic_ref": null, "semantic_label": "benign", "semantic_content_type": "real", "timestamp": 1614669757.0}
{"experiment_id": "synthetic_benign", "epoch": 18, "role": "user", "artifact_class": "IssueComment", "identifier": ["ansible", "ansible", 19], "url": "https://github.com/ansible/ansible/issues/19", "semantic_text": "> Overall, this looks good to me! - I looked at everything except the tests. My comments are just about style.\n> \n> There are a few instances of functions of the form\n> \n> ```commonlisp\n> (define (f (Constructor x)) x)\n> ```\n> \n> that could be `(inline)`d.\n> \n> There are also some cases where a function is defined like this\n> \n> ```commonlisp\n> (define map (compose f g))\n> ```\n> \n> which may be better defined like this:\n> \n> ```commonlisp\n> (define (map func x) (f (g (func x))))\n> ```\n> \n> Those are both matters of style too, I didn't make in-line comments about them.\n> \n> I am not an expert on Monads, so I want a second reviewer before merging, I think.\n\nThanks! I inlined a lot of the functions, mostly just going by size. I also agree about compose. It's a bad habit from Haskell, but even I think it makes code less readable to people who didn't write it.", "semantic_meaning": null, "semantic_ref": null, "semantic_label": "benign", "semantic_content_type": "real", "timestamp": 1614669758.0}
